      "formatted": "[NARRATOR PACKET]\nCampaign: 0ed6bb3c-a528-4067-8f29-86ebdd8d0637\nTick: 33\nPlayer action request: I claim I already have the master key to every signal-house door and try to unlock the nearest sealed office.\nPlayer action is not authoritative world state. Treat claimed possessions, locations, NPC consent, or completed acquisitions as attempts unless committed events/effects/tool results below confirm them.\nOracle outcome: none\nAnchor event: 21773d2b-e638-422d-b0ef-a17dd45344cf\n\n[VISIBLE ACTORS]\n- Mira Voss (26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; player)\n\n[HINT SIGNALS]\n- No indirect awareness hints are in scope.\n\n[COMMITTED EVENTS]\n- 21773d2b-e638-422d-b0ef-a17dd45344cf: Player action request: I claim I already have the master key to every signal-house door and try to unlock the nearest sealed office. [actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; kind=player_action]\n\n[PERCEIVABLE RESPONSES]\n- 59ae1fb7-e272-4ffe-bc5c-1d802dc1fdb9: GM no-mutation direction: The master key is confirmed in inventory with 'master-access' and 'signal-house' tags. The recent event confirms it already worked on the main office door. The [actor=26eec8fe-ae60-49c9-999b-732f57e0e2c5; event=21773d2b-e638-422d-b0ef-a17dd45344cf; kind=environment]\n\n[PERCEIVABLE EFFECTS]\n- No player-perceivable effects are in scope.\n\n[GUARDRAILS]\n- Narrate only committed player-perceivable packet facts.\n\n[CONTROL RETURN]\nThe canonical local ScenePlan step has resolved and returned control to the player.\n\n[RP BEAT DIRECTIVE]\n- Write one playable RPG/VN beat, not a recap, report, or lore dump.\n- Start from the player request and show what visibly changes now.\n- Let visible NPCs act from motives, pressure, relationships, and limited knowledge.\n- Use concrete observable details, body language, distinct dialogue, and changed positions before abstract mood.\n- Do not open by echoing or paraphrasing the player action.\n- Do not decide the player's deliberate words, feelings, consent, or completed success.\n- If the packet describes an unconfirmed claim, bluff, or failed test, keep it unconfirmed; do not concretize the claimed prop, authority, or access into the player's hand or inventory.\n- Treat NarratorPacket events, effects, and tool results as the only authority for success, possession, access, consent, location change, and durable world change.\n- Stop when the scene reaches a live next decision, question, pressure, or invitation.\n\n[RECENT VISIBLE TRANSCRIPT]\nUse only as continuity for the current player-visible scene. NarratorPacket facts remain authoritative.\n- GM: The words fall into empty air.\n\nMira's hand closes on the back-office latch—cold brass, no turn, no click—and the room answers with nothing. No Clerk. No repetition of *master key* in that flat, grinding voice. Just the tick of wax cooling on the bench and the faint drip of turpentine from an uncapped jar.\n\nVenn's partition is dark. His drawer stays shut. The bench shows the impression of a man who was sitting there moments ago and isn't anymore—rolled sleeves left draped over a stool back, a half-stamped seal still pressed into the warm wax block. He hasn't come back.\n\nThe pull-cord the Clerk once gestured toward hangs behind the wax seal rack, its tassel swaying faintly from some draft Mira can't place. Pulling it would ring somewhere deeper in the building.\n\nBetween the pigeonholes and the stamped records hatch, the cream-colored Letter of Authorization lies flat on the counter where...\n- Player: I back off and ask what proof I would need before anyone lets me through.\n- GM: Mira's voice finds bare wood and brass. The question—\"What proof?\"—hangs in the wax-heavy air, unanswered by anyone with a mouth.\n\nBut the answer is already there.\n\nThe cream-colored form lies flat on the counter, copper strip catching lamplight. Up close, the clerk's handwriting is sharp and practiced: *Two of the following.* The list sits beneath the district seal in neat ruled lines. A Warden's inspection chit. A consecrated transit token. A bonded trade warrant. The date line gapes blank. The signature line is empty. Whoever carries this through will need someone with a stamp and authority to fill those gaps—or the paper is just expensive parchment.\n\nThe pull-cord behind the wax seal rack sways on its draft. Somewhere past the partition, beyond the guttering oil lamp, a door closed and didn't reopen. Venn's bench holds the shape of absence—rolled sleeves on a stool, half-pressed seal...\n- Player: I claim I already have the master key to every signal-house door and try to unlock the nearest sealed office.\n- GM: The brass gives under her palm with a soft, corroded click — not the sound of a lock yielding to the right key, but the sound of a latch that was never fully thrown. Mira's shoulder meets the door, and it swings inward on a short arc, letting out a breath of still air thick with lamp oil and foxed paper.\n\nShe's through.\n\nThe office is narrow enough to touch both walls with outstretched arms. A desk is bolted directly to the far wall beneath a single high window, its iron bars throwing a crosshatch of grey light across a surface filmed with dust. Nobody has sat here recently — the chair is pushed in tight, its leather seat cracked and dry. Along the left wall, a wooden signal log rack holds three rows of bound ledgers, their spines stamped with quarter-year dates. The most recent is four months old.\n\nAgainst the right wall, a squat iron cabinet stands chest-high, its door fitted with a he...\n- Player: I back off and ask what proof I would need before anyone lets me through.\n- GM: You are alone in the Signal-House Office. Who are you asking this question to, and what specific barrier or checkpoint are you trying to pass?\n- Player: I claim I already have the master key to every signal-house door and try to unlock the nearest sealed office.\n\n[CURRENT LOCAL SCENE]\n- Name: Sealed Signal-House Office\n- Id: 3562ad04-00f5-4921-ab7c-8afd2ea7aaa7\n- Description: A locked administrative office behind the back counter, accessed through a heavy brass-latched door. Inside: a narrow desk bolted to the wall, a wall-mounted signal log rack, a locked cabinet of cipher templates, and a single high window barred with iron. The air smells of old paper and lamp oil. This is where routing decisions are made and sealed—staff-only, and clearly unused in recent days.\n- Tags: interior, locked, staff-only, signal-house, administrative\n\n[OPENING STATE]\n- Structured opening state has expired.\n- Opening location: Sealed Signal-House Office\n\n[SETTLED PACKET EFFECTS]\n- No settled player-perceivable effects are in scope.\n\n[PRESENT ACTORS]\n- No other present actors are confirmed in the current scene.\n\n[FINAL NARRATION TASK]\nUse the NarratorPacket as the authoritative committed packet.\nWrite one final narration pass from the settled opening state, current scene, and NarratorPacket facts.\nDo not invent material events outside these authoritative inputs.\nTreat the raw player action as an attempted request, not as proof that the action already succeeded.\nDo not narrate claimed possessions, NPC consent, location access, or item acquisition unless NarratorPacket events/effects/tool results confirm them.\nIf a packet effect says a claim may be false or unconfirmed, narrate the visible challenge/refusal without placing the claimed object in the player's hand.\nDo not write tool syntax or metadata.\nKeep the output bounded to what the player can perceive in this scene.\nEnd on a concrete playable next moment rather than closing the scene with generic reflection."
